[1] Case updates
- Wed 30 Jan 2019. Epidemiological situation report, DRC Ministry of Health
[in French, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://us13.campaign-archive.com/?u=89e5755d2cca4840b1af93176&id=0bb84dddaf

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri dated 29 Jan 2019:
- Since the beginning of the epidemic, the cumulative number of cases is 752 698 confirmed and 54 probable. In total, there were 465 deaths (411 confirmed and 54 probable) and 259 people cured.
- 187 suspected cases under investigation.
- 9 new confirmed cases, including 8 in Katwa and 1 in Beni (report of 28 Jan 2019).
- 4 new confirmed case deaths, including 3 community deaths in Katwa, 1 death at the CTE of Butembo
- 1 new person healed out of Butembo CTE.

News of the response
Vaccination
-----------
- Since the beginning of vaccination on 8 Aug 2018, 69 827 people have been vaccinated, including 20 241 in Beni, 16 390 in Katwa, 7860 in Butembo, 6008 in Mabalako, 2626 in Kalunguta, 2080 in Komanda, 1911 in Goma, 1755 in Oicha, 1663 in Mandima, 1157 in Karisimbi, 877 in Vuhovi, 873 in Kayina, 842 in Kyondo, 750 in Masereka, 700 in Lubero, 599 in Mutwanga, 560 in Rutshuru, 527 in Nyankunde, 524 in Biena, 442 in Musienene, 434 in Bunia, 355 to Tchomia, 167 to Kirotshe, 125 to Nyiragongo, 114 to Alimbongo, 159 to Mangurujipa, 45 to Watsa (Haut-Uele) and 13 to Kisangani.

- The only vaccine to be used in this outbreak is the rVSV-ZEBOV vaccine, manufactured by the pharmaceutical group Merck, following approval by the Ethics Committee in its decision of 19 May 2018.

Preventive measures in Watsa (Haut-Uele)
----------------------------------------
- The Minister of Health, Dr. Oly Ilunga Kalenga, is in Watsa, Haut-Uele province, since Tue 29 Jan 2019 to supervise the prevention activities following the detection of a confirmed case in Katwa, from Watsa, Sat 26 Jan 2019.

- He is [the confirmed case] a young trader living in Watsa who is used to going back and forth between Watsa and Butembo. In-depth investigations revealed that the trader was contaminated during his stay in Katwa and not in Watsa. However, as a precautionary measure, a team of epidemiologists, vaccinators and infection prevention and control experts were dispatched to Watsa to vaccinate their relatives and front-line health workers, as well as to decontaminate their home and the center in which he had been hospitalized.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteurs Kunihiko Iizuka and Mary Marshall

[The case of the trader highlights the difficulty of contact tracing. Kudos to the epidemiologists for determining the point of infection. It is good the relatives were vaccinated in Watsu, even though that turned out not to be the origin of the infection, but no doubt the trader had many contacts en route between both locations. Those individuals are at risk.

Helen Branswell (https://twitter.com/HelenBranswell)
#Ebola thread: 2 more health workers have been infected, according to this week's situation report from @WHOAFRO. That makes 63 infected health workers since the outbreak began; 21 have died.

2. The number of children orphaned by this #Ebola outbreak continues to climb, according to @UNICEF's most recent situation report. The agency has helped 601 orphaned or separated children since the start of the epidemic.

4. Neat idea: Community resistance, which sometimes spills over into violence, continues to hamper the response. One approach to getting people to trust #Ebola treatment centers has been to give tours, to dispel rumors.

5. Occupancy at #Ebola treatment centers in key locations is high. Really high.

#DRC does some #Ebola vaccinating in a place called Watsa, in Haut-Uele province, after a traveling trader tests positive for Ebola. Watsa is more than 300 mi (more than 500 km) NE of Butembo, where he is believed to have been infected. A new distant front in this war would be bad.
- Mod LK]

