[3] Preparedness and prevention
-Thu 24 Jan 2019. Following a full simulation exercise, a joint monitoring mission is deployed in Rwanda
[All Africa, abridged, edited]
https://allafrica.com/stories/201901240562.html

Following the Full Simulation Exercise (FSIMEX) conducted in Rwanda at the beginning of January 2019 to assess EVD readiness/preparedness and response capacity in the country, an external Joint Monitoring Mission (JMM) team comprising of WHO specialists and partners relevant to the EVD preparedness efforts in Rwanda was deployed in the country.

The scope of the JMM was to provide additional support to the Republic of Rwanda to:
1. Strengthen its preparedness should there be introduction of EVD into the country;
2. Review the preparedness and readiness activities already undertaken, this was based on the findings from the full simulation exercise (FSIMEX) conducted and the recommendations from the preparedness Joint Monitoring mission team;
3. Advocate for prioritization and support to national EVD preparedness capacity and capability to ensure operational readiness for response to a potential importation of an Ebola Virus Disease (EVD) case;

Given the geographical position of Rwanda as landlocked country sharing borders with Uganda, Burundi, Tanzania and DRC, POEs were determined to be critical.

The Preparedness Joint Monitoring Mission recommended that there was a critical need for more support for the Rwandan Refugee Transit Centers. A number of key preparedness measures will also have to be scaled up, not only at POEs, but also District Hospitals and Ebola Treatment Centers.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

- Tue 29 Jan 2019. Dr. Michael Yao interview, prevention of Ebola spread
[Radio Okapi, in French, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://www.radiookapi.net/2019/01/29/actualite/sante/dr-michel-yao-tant-quon-naura-pas-controle-ebola-dans-toutes-les-zones

Dr. Michel Yao: "As long as we have not controlled Ebola in all areas, none of the areas are safe"

Dr. Michel Yao is Head of Emergency Operations for the World Health Organization (WHO) / Africa and Ebola response coordinator in North Kivu and Ituri notes that control of Ebola virus disease in infected areas will allow other unaffected provinces to be sheltered. It encourages people to follow the measures recommended by health authorities to fight Ebola.

"We must continue efforts. That means you cannot let your guard down. When it improves, we must continue vigilance, we must have the entire community aware to eliminate this epidemic. It also shows that until the epidemic is controlled in all areas, none of the areas are safe, including even those that are not in North Kivu or Ituri province, warned Dr. Michel Yao.

He also notes that this epidemic is very dangerous. "Since the beginning of this epidemic, we have about 18 health zones that are affected, including 14 in North Kivu. As for the numbers, yesterday [Mon 28 Jan 2019] we were more than 736 cases and 415 deaths. This shows an epidemic of exceptional magnitude. It is currently the biggest epidemic after that of West Africa," warned Mr. Yao.

For him, the epidemic of Ebola occurs in an exceptional context of security, but also in a context where the populations do not know the disease, in a context of reluctance or resistance even rather exceptional.

"It's a dynamic population that moves for economic reasons, but also for security reasons. There is also the acceptation of the answer. It is a scary disease and therefore people are reluctant. And this reluctance holds back an effective response. These include the non-acceptance of the secure burial, it is also the refusal of vaccination that are all measures that can control this outbreak, "he added.

According to Dr. Michel Yao, the mobility of the population favors the spread of this epidemic.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

